    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Double duct-flute developed by William Bainbridge of London in the early 19th century, featuring six, occasionally seven, fingerholes on each side, and one or no thumbholes. It allowed the player to play in two-part harmony with one hand on each duct.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046893/New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians (2001)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Flageolets desarrollados por William Bainbridge, de Londres, a comienzos del siglo XIX, con seis, y ocasionalmente siete, orificios para los dedos y otro para el pulgar, o ninguno.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Dubbele snavelfluiten die aan het begin van de 19de eeuw zijn ontworpen door William Bainbridge uit Londen met zes of soms zeven toongaten aan elke kant, en één of geen duimgaten. De speler kon hierdoor tweestemmig spelen met één hand op elke fluit.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>雙重式的管風笛，是由倫敦的威廉‧班恩布里吉(William Bainbridge)在十九世紀所發展出來的，每一側有著六個、通常是七個指孔，並且有一個大拇指孔或者是都沒有。它讓彈奏者可以只用一隻手在每一道風導管上彈奏出二部合奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Doppelkernspaltflöte, entwickelt von William Bainbridge in London im frühen 19. Jahrhundert, mit sechs, gelegentlich sieben Grifflöchern auf jeder Seite und einem oder keinem Daumenloch. Sie erlaubte dem Spieler zweistimmig zu spielen, mit jeweils einer Hand auf jeder Röhre.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
